<paragraph id="8B8D36E5A6434A10FF2FF9C73129F9F6" blockId="45.[151,517,1554,1580]" box="[151,517,1554,1580]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
<heading id="D0C58189A6434A10FF2FF9C73129F9F6" bold="true" box="[151,517,1554,1580]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" reason="1">
<emphasis id="B946EAF7A6434A10FF2FF9C73129F9F6" bold="true" box="[151,517,1554,1580]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
<taxonomicName id="4C324D66A6434A10FF2FF9C7329DF9F6" authorityName="Li &amp; Sattler" authorityYear="2012" box="[151,433,1554,1580]" class="Insecta" family="Gelechiidae" genus="Mesophleps" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="truncatella">
<emphasis id="B946EAF7A6434A10FF2FF9C7329DF9F6" bold="true" box="[151,433,1554,1580]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Mesophleps truncatella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-group
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8D36E5A6434A10FF2FF98C3744F94F" blockId="45.[151,1436,1625,1973]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Labial palpus recurved, segment 2 distally thicker than at base, with dorsal brush of long erectile scales, brown with white distal ring; segment 3 about as long as 2, white, sometimes with black apex.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C328656EA6434A10FF7FF9743207F86F" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B8D36E5A6434A10FF7FF97437AAF8FC" blockId="45.[151,1436,1625,1973]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis id="B946EAF7A6434A10FF7FF9743219F960" bold="true" box="[199,309,1697,1722]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Genitalia</emphasis>
<specimenCount id="9D34FD6CA6434A10FEFBF974327AF96E" box="[323,342,1697,1716]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" type="male">♂</specimenCount>
(
<figureCitation id="13092A60A6434A10FED2F97432D5F963" box="[362,505,1697,1721]" captionStart="FIGURES 78–82" captionStartId="72.[151,264,1928,1951]" captionTargetBox="[190,1400,188,1887]" captionTargetId="figure-71@72.[182,1406,169,1897]" captionTargetPageId="72" captionText="FIGURES 78–82. Male genitalia of Mesophleps spp. 78. M. parvella sp. nov. paratype, slide no. 30915; 79. M. aspina sp. nov. holotype, slide no. 30960; 80. M. truncatella sp. nov. holotype, slide no. 30889; 81. M. undulatella sp. nov. holotype, slide no. 30966; 82. M. geodes (Meyrick), slide no. 30939." pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Figs 80, 81</figureCitation>
). Uncus large, broader than tegumen, expanded laterally, distally truncated or concave. Gnathos hooks very strong, widely separated, bases connected by narrow, gently curved, sclerotized ribbon. Tegumen relatively short, anterior emargination variable; pedunculi long, simple, curved. Valva unremarkable. Vinculum rounded, distal portion narrow or wide. Phallus typical of genus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8D36E5A6434A10FF71F8E43207F86F" blockId="45.[151,1436,1625,1973]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis id="B946EAF7A6434A10FF71F8E4321BF890" bold="true" box="[201,311,1841,1866]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Genitalia</emphasis>
<specimenCount id="9D34FD6CA6434A10FEFEF8E43275F89E" box="[326,345,1841,1860]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
(
<figureCitation id="13092A60A6434A10FED6F8E43135F893" box="[366,537,1841,1865]" captionStart="FIGURES 106–111" captionStartId="77.[151,264,1926,1949]" captionTargetBox="[209,1358,192,1880]" captionTargetId="figure-75@77.[181,1405,177,1905]" captionTargetPageId="77" captionText="FIGURES 106–111. Female genitalia of Mesophleps spp. 106. M. nairobiensis Li &amp; Zheng, slide no. 30825; 107. M. coffeae sp. nov. paratype, slide no. 30796; 108. M. truncatella sp. nov. paratype, slide no. 30891; 109. M. undulatella sp. nov. paratype, slide no. 30965; 110. M. geodes (Meyrick), slide no. 30937; 111. M. catericta (Meyrick), slide no. 30973." pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Figs 108, 109</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="13092A60A6434A10FD95F8E431B6F893" box="[557,666,1841,1865]" captionStart="FIGURES 131–142" captionStartId="80.[151,264,1833,1856]" captionTargetBox="[196,1376,213,1766]" captionTargetId="figure-127@80.[181,1405,193,1813]" captionTargetPageId="80" captionText="FIGURES 131–142. Female segment VIII of Mesophleps spp. 131. M. ochracella (Turati), slide no. 30982; 132. M. unguella sp. nov. paratype, slide no. 30956; 133. M. gigantella sp. nov. paratype, slide no. 15836; 134. M. sp. (Yunnan), slide no. L95070; 135. M. albilinella (Park), slide no. L03077; 136. M. nairobiensis Li &amp; Zheng, slide no. 30825; 137. M. coffeae sp. nov. paratype, slide no. 30796; 138. M. parvella sp. nov. paratype, slide no. 30951; 139. M. truncatella sp. nov. paratype, slide no. 30891; 140. M. undulatella sp. nov. paratype, slide no. 30965; 141. M. geodes (Meyrick), slide no. 30937; 142. M. catericta (Meyrick), slide no. 30973." pageId="45" pageNumber="46">139, 140</figureCitation>
). Dorso-posterior margin of segment VIII with pair of strongly sclerotized pits; sclerotized antrum variable; ductus bursae short, at most twice length of apophyses anteriores; ductus seminalis from small bulge in posterior part of corpus bursae (
<taxonomicName id="4C324D66A6434A10FC0CF8AC371FF84B" authorityName="Li &amp; Sattler" authorityYear="2012" box="[948,1075,1913,1937]" class="Insecta" family="Gelechiidae" genus="Mesophleps" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undulatella">
<emphasis id="B946EAF7A6434A10FC0CF8AC371FF84B" box="[948,1075,1913,1937]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">undulatella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) or very close to ductus bursae (
<taxonomicName id="4C324D66A6434A10FF18F8483237F86F" authorityName="Li &amp; Sattler" authorityYear="2012" box="[160,283,1949,1973]" class="Insecta" family="Gelechiidae" genus="Mesophleps" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="truncatella">
<emphasis id="B946EAF7A6434A10FF18F8483237F86F" box="[160,283,1949,1973]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">truncatella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C328656EA6404A13FF71FF4D328BFF2D" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B8D36E5A6404A13FF71FF4D328BFF2D" blockId="46.[151,1436,151,320]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis id="B946EAF7A6404A13FF71FF4D3210FF6A" bold="true" box="[201,316,152,176]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" reason="1">Remarks.</emphasis>
Members of this group differ from other 
<taxonomicName id="4C324D66A6404A13FCAEFF4D30B0FF6A" authorityName="Hubner" authorityYear="1825" box="[790,924,152,176]" class="Insecta" family="Gelechiidae" genus="Mesophleps" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B946EAF7A6404A13FCAEFF4D30B0FF6A" box="[790,924,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Mesophleps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the male genitalia in the broad, somewhat atypical uncus and, in the female genitalia, in the presence of conspicuous sclerotized pits on the dorso-posterior margin of segment VIII.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C328656EA6404A13FF71FED6303CFEC6" box="[201,784,259,284]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" type="biology_ecology">
